Brief Description.
Length 
2.16–2.90 mm
, width 
1.62–2.20 mm
. Form (
Fig. 1a, b
) oval, dorsoventrally somewhat flattened to very weakly convex, posterior margin of elytra broadly rounded to subtruncate, leaving abdominal apex slightly exposed. Head orange yellow, eyes brilliant metallic green in live specimens, pronotum orange yellow to reddish brown, basal margin of pronotum usually medially infuscate to some degree. Elytra pale creamy yellow, with three longitudinal black vittae, one on each elytron in a mid-dorsal position not reaching apex and one along sutural line reaching apex (
Fig. 1b
), elytral stripes apically joined together with a short stem, forming a trident shaped marking in nominate form (
Fig. 1a
); elytral apex narrowly bordered black. Prosternal carinae (

Fig. 
1g

) convergent towards anterior, lacking a distinct stem. Abdomen (
Fig. 1h
) with six visible ventrites, abdominal postcoxal line apically incomplete (
Fig. 1j
), ventrite 6 with posterior margin emarginate in male (
Fig. 1h
) and broadly arcuate in female (
Fig. 1i
). Male genitalia (
Fig. 1n–p, 1r–t
) with penis guide asymmetrical (
Fig. 1o, r
), penis strongly curved with a distinct capsule (
Fig. 1p, s
), penis apex as illustrated (
Fig. 1q, t
). Female genitalia with coxites (
Fig. 1k
) transverse, spermathecal capsule stout with a basal appendix bearing a bulbous, almost globular distal process (
Fig. 1l, m
).

Immature stages. The larva ( Fig. 3a–f ) is fleshy, somewhat spindle shaped with a median bulge and narrowed at both ends. It is usually greyish with powdery wax coating or pruinosity on the dorsal surface ( Fig. 3b–f ) and rarely pinkish ( Fig. 3a ) with white waxy coating. The larvae have a characteristic mode of feeding and usually burrow into the ovisacs of mealybugs ( Fig. 3e ) and also feed on the other stages. The pupa (
Fig. 3g
) is yellowish to pinkish red in colour and enclosed in medially longitudinally split open larval exuvium and is similar to the type found in the tribes Noviini and Chilocorini .

Prey / associated habitat. It is primarily a predator of mealybugs ( Pseudococcidae ) ( Fig. 4 ), but also recorded in association with aphids (
Rafi et al. 2005
;
Chakrabarti et al . 2012
;
Iqbal et al . 2019
). In South India , it is commonly collected in association with various mealybugs and aphids infesting brinjal (
Solanum melongena
L.) ( Chatterjee 1954 ) and parthenium ( Parthenium hysterophorus L.) (unpublished data).
